   "reasoning": "To implement the Lemmings game behavior described, we need a Moore state machine with two states: walking left and walking right. The state transitions depend on the bump_left and bump_right inputs. When a bump occurs (either on left or right or both), the Lemming changes direction. We\'ll use areset to asynchronously reset the machine to walk left. Since this is a Moore machine, outputs depend only on the current state. The implementation will use two states (logic values 0 and 1) to represent walk_left and walk_right. We\'ll use a synchronous reset with areset asserting high to reset the state to walk left. In the state transition logic, we check the bump conditions to determine if a flip in direction is needed. The output logic reflects the current state. We ensure all signals are declared as logic, and use always @(*) for combinational logic.",\n    "module": "module TopModule (\\n    input clk,\\n    input areset,\\n    input bump_left,\\n    input bump_right,\\n    output walk_left,\\n    output walk_right\\n);\\n\\n    // Define states\\n    localparam WALK_LEFT = 1\'b0;\\n    localparam WALK_RIGHT = 1\'b1;\\n\\n    // State register\\n    logic current_state;\\n    logic next_state;\\n\\n    // Sequential logic for state register\\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\\n        if (areset)\\n            current_state <= WALK_LEFT;\\n        else\\n            current_state <= next_state;\\n    end\\n\\n    // Combinational logic for next state\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        if (bump_left || bump_right) begin\\n            // Change direction based on current state\\n            if (current_state == WALK_LEFT)\\n                next_state = WALK_RIGHT;\\n            else\\n                next_state = WALK_LEFT;\\n        end else begin\\n            // No change in direction\\n            next_state = current_state;\\n        end\\n    end\\n\\n    // Output logic for walk_left and walk_right\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        if (current_state == WALK_LEFT)\\n            {walk_left, walk_right} = 2\'b10;\\n        else\\n            {walk_left, walk_right} = 2\'b01;\\n    end\\n\\nendmodule"\n}')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe error below has been reported by the format tool:\n<format_error>\n{\n    "stdout": "",\n    "stderr": "./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:43: error: walk_left is not a valid l-value in TopModule.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:6:      : walk_left is declared here as wire.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:43: error: walk_right is not a valid l-value in TopModule.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:7:      : walk_right is declared here as wire.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:45: error: walk_left is not a valid l-value in TopModule.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:6:      : walk_left is declared here as wire.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:45: error: walk_right is not a valid l-value in TopModule.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob127_lemmings1/rtl.sv:7:      : walk_right is declared here as wire.\\n4 error(s) during elaboration.\\n"\n}\n</format_error>\nTo understand the error message better, we offered a version of generated module with line number:\n<module_with_lineno>\n1: module TopModule (\n2:     input clk,\n3:     input areset,\n4:     input bump_left,\n5:     input bump_right,\n6:     output walk_left,\n7:     output walk_right\n8: );\n9: \n10:     // Define states\n11:     localparam WALK_LEFT = 1\'b0;\n12:     localparam WALK_RIGHT = 1\'b1;\n13: \n14:     // State register\n15:     logic current_state;\n16:     logic nex